3348 
3349  /*--- Set the value of the second viscosity and compute the divergence
3350  term in the viscous normal stresses. ---*/
3351  const su2double lambda = -TWO3*Viscosity;
3352  const su2double lamDivTerm = lambda*divVel;
3353 
3354  /*--- Compute the viscous stress tensor and minus the heatflux vector. ---*/
3355  const su2double tauxx = 2.0*Viscosity*dudx + lamDivTerm;
3356  const su2double tauyy = 2.0*Viscosity*dvdy + lamDivTerm;
3357  const su2double tauxy = Viscosity*(dudy + dvdx);
3358 
3359  const su2double qx = kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDx;
3360  const su2double qy = kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDy;
3361 
3362  /* Compute the relative velocities w.r.t. the grid. */
3363  const su2double uRel = u - gridVel[0];
3364  const su2double vRel = v - gridVel[1];
3365 
3366  /* Compute the viscous normal stress minus the pressure. */
3367  const su2double tauxxMP = tauxx - Pressure;
3368  const su2double tauyyMP = tauyy - Pressure;
3369 
3370  /* Set the pointer for the fluxes in this integration point. */
3371  su2double *flux = fluxes + nDim*iNPad + llNVar;
3372 
3373  /*--- Fluxes in r-direction. */
3374  const su2double Ur = uRel*wDrdx + vRel*wDrdy;
3375 
3376  flux[0] = sol[0]*Ur;
3377  flux[1] = sol[1]*Ur - tauxxMP*wDrdx - tauxy*wDrdy;
3378  flux[2] = sol[2]*Ur - tauxy*wDrdx - tauyyMP*wDrdy;
3379  flux[3] = sol[3]*Ur - (u*tauxxMP + v*tauxy + qx)*wDrdx
3380  - (u*tauxy + v*tauyyMP + qy)*wDrdy;
3381 
3382  /*--- Fluxes in s-direction. */
3383  flux = flux + NPad;
3384  const su2double Us = uRel*wDsdx + vRel*wDsdy;
3385 
3386  flux[0] = sol[0]*Us;
3387  flux[1] = sol[1]*Us - tauxxMP*wDsdx - tauxy*wDsdy;
3388  flux[2] = sol[2]*Us - tauxy*wDsdx - tauyyMP*wDsdy;
3389  flux[3] = sol[3]*Us - (u*tauxxMP + v*tauxy + qx)*wDsdx
3390  - (u*tauxy + v*tauyyMP + qy)*wDsdy;
3391 
3392  /*--- If needed, compute the body forces in this integration point.
3393  Note that the source terms are multiplied with minus the
3394  integration weight in order to be consistent with the
3395  formulation of the residual. Note that for the energy source
3396  term the absolute velocity must be taken and not the
3397  relative. ---*/
3398  if( body_force ) {
3399  su2double *source = sources + iNPad + llNVar;
3400  const su2double weightJac = weights[i]*Jac;
3401 
3402  source[0] = 0.0;
3403  source[1] = -weightJac*body_force_vector[0];
3404  source[2] = -weightJac*body_force_vector[1];
3405  source[3] = -weightJac*(u*body_force_vector[0] + v*body_force_vector[1]);
3406  }
3407  }
3408  }
3409 
3410  break;
3411  }
3412 
3413  /*----------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3414 
3415  case 3: {
3416 
3417  /* 3D simulation. Loop over the chunk of elements and loop over the
3418  integration points of the elements to compute the fluxes. */
3419  for(unsigned short ll=0; ll<llEnd; ++ll) {
3420  const unsigned short llNVar = ll*nVar;
3421  const unsigned long lInd = l + ll;
3422 
3423  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
3424  const unsigned short iNPad = i*NPad;
3425 
3426  /* Easier storage of the metric terms and grid velocities in this
3427  integration point and compute the inverse of the Jacobian. */
3428  const su2double *metricTerms = volElem[lInd].metricTerms.data()
3429  + i*nMetricPerPoint;
3430  const su2double *gridVel = volElem[lInd].gridVelocities.data() + i*nDim;
3431  const su2double Jac = metricTerms[0];
3432  const su2double JacInv = 1.0/Jac;
3433 
3434  /* Compute the true metric terms in this integration point. */
3435  const su2double drdx = JacInv*metricTerms[1];
3436  const su2double drdy = JacInv*metricTerms[2];
3437  const su2double drdz = JacInv*metricTerms[3];
3438 
3439  const su2double dsdx = JacInv*metricTerms[4];
3440  const su2double dsdy = JacInv*metricTerms[5];
3441  const su2double dsdz = JacInv*metricTerms[6];
3442 
3443  const su2double dtdx = JacInv*metricTerms[7];
3444  const su2double dtdy = JacInv*metricTerms[8];
3445  const su2double dtdz = JacInv*metricTerms[9];
3446 
3447  /* Compute the metric terms multiplied by minus the integration weight.
3448  The minus sign comes from the integration by parts in the weak
3449  formulation. */
3450  const su2double wDrdx = -weights[i]*metricTerms[1];
3451  const su2double wDrdy = -weights[i]*metricTerms[2];
3452  const su2double wDrdz = -weights[i]*metricTerms[3];
3453 
3454  const su2double wDsdx = -weights[i]*metricTerms[4];
3455  const su2double wDsdy = -weights[i]*metricTerms[5];
3456  const su2double wDsdz = -weights[i]*metricTerms[6];
3457 
3458  const su2double wDtdx = -weights[i]*metricTerms[7];
3459  const su2double wDtdy = -weights[i]*metricTerms[8];
3460  const su2double wDtdz = -weights[i]*metricTerms[9];
3461 
3462  /* Easier storage of the location where the solution data of this
3463  integration point starts. */
3464  const su2double *sol = solAndGradInt + iNPad + llNVar;
3465  const su2double *dSolDr = sol + offDeriv;
3466  const su2double *dSolDs = dSolDr + offDeriv;
3467  const su2double *dSolDt = dSolDs + offDeriv;
3468 
3469  /*--- Compute the Cartesian gradients of the independent solution
3470  variables from the gradients in parametric coordinates and the
3471  metric terms in this integration point. ---*/
3472  const su2double dRhoDx = dSolDr[0]*drdx + dSolDs[0]*dsdx + dSolDt[0]*dtdx;
3473  const su2double dRhoUDx = dSolDr[1]*drdx + dSolDs[1]*dsdx + dSolDt[1]*dtdx;
3474  const su2double dRhoVDx = dSolDr[2]*drdx + dSolDs[2]*dsdx + dSolDt[2]*dtdx;
3475  const su2double dRhoWDx = dSolDr[3]*drdx + dSolDs[3]*dsdx + dSolDt[3]*dtdx;
3476  const su2double dRhoEDx = dSolDr[4]*drdx + dSolDs[4]*dsdx + dSolDt[4]*dtdx;
3477 
3478  const su2double dRhoDy = dSolDr[0]*drdy + dSolDs[0]*dsdy + dSolDt[0]*dtdy;
3479  const su2double dRhoUDy = dSolDr[1]*drdy + dSolDs[1]*dsdy + dSolDt[1]*dtdy;
3480  const su2double dRhoVDy = dSolDr[2]*drdy + dSolDs[2]*dsdy + dSolDt[2]*dtdy;
3481  const su2double dRhoWDy = dSolDr[3]*drdy + dSolDs[3]*dsdy + dSolDt[3]*dtdy;
3482  const su2double dRhoEDy = dSolDr[4]*drdy + dSolDs[4]*dsdy + dSolDt[4]*dtdy;
3483 
3484  const su2double dRhoDz = dSolDr[0]*drdz + dSolDs[0]*dsdz + dSolDt[0]*dtdz;
3485  const su2double dRhoUDz = dSolDr[1]*drdz + dSolDs[1]*dsdz + dSolDt[1]*dtdz;
3486  const su2double dRhoVDz = dSolDr[2]*drdz + dSolDs[2]*dsdz + dSolDt[2]*dtdz;
3487  const su2double dRhoWDz = dSolDr[3]*drdz + dSolDs[3]*dsdz + dSolDt[3]*dtdz;
3488  const su2double dRhoEDz = dSolDr[4]*drdz + dSolDs[4]*dsdz + dSolDt[4]*dtdz;
3489 
3490  /*--- Compute the velocities and static energy in this integration point. ---*/
3491  const su2double rhoInv = 1.0/sol[0];
3492  const su2double u = sol[1]*rhoInv;
3493  const su2double v = sol[2]*rhoInv;
3494  const su2double w = sol[3]*rhoInv;
3495  const su2double TotalEnergy = sol[4]*rhoInv;
3496  const su2double StaticEnergy = TotalEnergy - 0.5*(u*u + v*v + w*w);
3497 
3498  /*--- Compute the Cartesian gradients of the velocities and static energy
3499  in this integration point and also the divergence of the velocity. ---*/
3500  const su2double dudx = rhoInv*(dRhoUDx - u*dRhoDx);
3501  const su2double dudy = rhoInv*(dRhoUDy - u*dRhoDy);
3502  const su2double dudz = rhoInv*(dRhoUDz - u*dRhoDz);
3503 
3504  const su2double dvdx = rhoInv*(dRhoVDx - v*dRhoDx);
3505  const su2double dvdy = rhoInv*(dRhoVDy - v*dRhoDy);
3506  const su2double dvdz = rhoInv*(dRhoVDz - v*dRhoDz);
3507 
3508  const su2double dwdx = rhoInv*(dRhoWDx - w*dRhoDx);
3509  const su2double dwdy = rhoInv*(dRhoWDy - w*dRhoDy);
3510  const su2double dwdz = rhoInv*(dRhoWDz - w*dRhoDz);
3511 
3512  const su2double dStaticEnergyDx = rhoInv*(dRhoEDx - TotalEnergy*dRhoDx)
3513  - u*dudx - v*dvdx - w*dwdx;
3514  const su2double dStaticEnergyDy = rhoInv*(dRhoEDy - TotalEnergy*dRhoDy)
3515  - u*dudy - v*dvdy - w*dwdy;
3516  const su2double dStaticEnergyDz = rhoInv*(dRhoEDz - TotalEnergy*dRhoDz)
3517  - u*dudz - v*dvdz - w*dwdz;
3518 
3519  const su2double divVel = dudx + dvdy + dwdz;
3520 
3521  /*--- Compute the pressure and the laminar viscosity. ---*/
3522  FluidModel->SetTDState_rhoe(sol[0], StaticEnergy);
3523  const su2double Pressure = FluidModel->GetPressure();
3524  const su2double ViscosityLam = FluidModel->GetLaminarViscosity();
3525 
3526  /*--- If an SGS model is used the eddy viscosity must be computed. ---*/
3527  su2double ViscosityTurb = 0.0;
3528  if( SGSModelUsed ) {
3529  const su2double lenScale = volElem[lInd].lenScale/nPoly;
3530  ViscosityTurb = SGSModel->ComputeEddyViscosity_3D(sol[0], dudx, dudy, dudz,
3531  dvdx, dvdy, dvdz, dwdx,
3532  dwdy, dwdz, lenScale,
3533  volElem[lInd].wallDistance[i]);
3534  }
3535 
3536  /* Compute the total viscosity and heat conductivity. Note that the heat
3537  conductivity is divided by the Cv, because gradients of internal energy
3538  are computed and not temperature. */
3539  const su2double Viscosity = ViscosityLam + ViscosityTurb;
3540  const su2double kOverCv = ViscosityLam *factHeatFlux_Lam
3541  + ViscosityTurb*factHeatFlux_Turb;
3542 
3543  /*--- Set the value of the second viscosity and compute the divergence
3544  term in the viscous normal stresses. ---*/
3545  const su2double lambda = -TWO3*Viscosity;
3546  const su2double lamDivTerm = lambda*divVel;
3547 
3548  /*--- Compute the viscous stress tensor and minus the heatflux vector. ---*/
3549  const su2double tauxx = 2.0*Viscosity*dudx + lamDivTerm;
3550  const su2double tauyy = 2.0*Viscosity*dvdy + lamDivTerm;
3551  const su2double tauzz = 2.0*Viscosity*dwdz + lamDivTerm;
3552 
3553  const su2double tauxy = Viscosity*(dudy + dvdx);
3554  const su2double tauxz = Viscosity*(dudz + dwdx);
3555  const su2double tauyz = Viscosity*(dvdz + dwdy);
3556 
3557  const su2double qx = kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDx;
3558  const su2double qy = kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDy;
3559  const su2double qz = kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDz;
3560 
3561  /* Compute the relative velocities w.r.t. the grid. */
3562  const su2double uRel = u - gridVel[0];
3563  const su2double vRel = v - gridVel[1];
3564  const su2double wRel = w - gridVel[2];
3565 
3566  /* Compute the viscous normal stress minus the pressure. */
3567  const su2double tauxxMP = tauxx - Pressure;
3568  const su2double tauyyMP = tauyy - Pressure;
3569  const su2double tauzzMP = tauzz - Pressure;
3570 
3571  /* Set the pointer for the fluxes in this integration point. */
3572  su2double *flux = fluxes + nDim*iNPad + llNVar;
3573 
3574  /*--- Fluxes in r-direction. */
3575  const su2double Ur = uRel*wDrdx + vRel*wDrdy + wRel*wDrdz;
3576 
3577  flux[0] = sol[0]*Ur;
3578  flux[1] = sol[1]*Ur - tauxxMP*wDrdx - tauxy*wDrdy - tauxz*wDrdz;
3579  flux[2] = sol[2]*Ur - tauxy*wDrdx - tauyyMP*wDrdy - tauyz*wDrdz;
3580  flux[3] = sol[3]*Ur - tauxz*wDrdx - tauyz*wDrdy - tauzzMP*wDrdz;
3581  flux[4] = sol[4]*Ur - (u*tauxxMP + v*tauxy + w*tauxz + qx)*wDrdx
3582  - (u*tauxy + v*tauyyMP + w*tauyz + qy)*wDrdy
3583  - (u*tauxz + v*tauyz + w*tauzzMP + qz)*wDrdz;
3584 
3585  /*--- Fluxes in s-direction. */
3586  flux = flux + NPad;
3587  const su2double Us = uRel*wDsdx + vRel*wDsdy + wRel*wDsdz;
3588 
3589  flux[0] = sol[0]*Us;
3590  flux[1] = sol[1]*Us - tauxxMP*wDsdx - tauxy*wDsdy - tauxz*wDsdz;
3591  flux[2] = sol[2]*Us - tauxy*wDsdx - tauyyMP*wDsdy - tauyz*wDsdz;
3592  flux[3] = sol[3]*Us - tauxz*wDsdx - tauyz*wDsdy - tauzzMP*wDsdz;
3593  flux[4] = sol[4]*Us - (u*tauxxMP + v*tauxy + w*tauxz + qx)*wDsdx
3594  - (u*tauxy + v*tauyyMP + w*tauyz + qy)*wDsdy
3595  - (u*tauxz + v*tauyz + w*tauzzMP + qz)*wDsdz;
3596 
3597  /*--- Fluxes in t-direction. */
3598  flux = flux + NPad;
3599  const su2double Ut = uRel*wDtdx + vRel*wDtdy + wRel*wDtdz;
3600 
3601  flux[0] = sol[0]*Ut;
3602  flux[1] = sol[1]*Ut - tauxxMP*wDtdx - tauxy*wDtdy - tauxz*wDtdz;
3603  flux[2] = sol[2]*Ut - tauxy*wDtdx - tauyyMP*wDtdy - tauyz*wDtdz;
3604  flux[3] = sol[3]*Ut - tauxz*wDtdx - tauyz*wDtdy - tauzzMP*wDtdz;
3605  flux[4] = sol[4]*Ut - (u*tauxxMP + v*tauxy + w*tauxz + qx)*wDtdx
3606  - (u*tauxy + v*tauyyMP + w*tauyz + qy)*wDtdy
3607  - (u*tauxz + v*tauyz + w*tauzzMP + qz)*wDtdz;
3608 
3609  /*--- If needed, compute the body forces in this integration point.
3610  Note that the source terms are multiplied with minus the
3611  integration weight in order to be consistent with the
3612  formulation of the residual. Note that for the energy source
3613  term the absolute velocity must be taken and not the
3614  relative. ---*/
3615  if( body_force ) {
3616  su2double *source = sources + iNPad + llNVar;
3617  const su2double weightJac = weights[i]*Jac;
3618 
3619  source[0] = 0.0;
3620  source[1] = -weightJac*body_force_vector[0];
3621  source[2] = -weightJac*body_force_vector[1];
3622  source[3] = -weightJac*body_force_vector[2];
3623  source[4] = -weightJac*(u*body_force_vector[0] + v*body_force_vector[1]
3624  + w*body_force_vector[2]);
3625  }
3626  }
3627  }
3628 
3629  break;
3630  }
3631  }
3632 
3633  /* Initialize addSourceTerms to body_force. The value of addSourceTerms
3634  is set to true when a manufactured solution is computed. */
3635  bool addSourceTerms = body_force;
3636 
3637  /* Check whether or not a manufactured solution is used. */
3638  if( VerificationSolution ) {
3639  if( VerificationSolution->IsManufacturedSolution() ) {
3640 
3641  /*--- For the manufactured solutions a source term must be added. If a
3642  standard source term has not been specified, initialize the source
3643  terms to zero and set addSourceTerms to true. ---*/
3644  addSourceTerms = true;
3645  if( !body_force ) {
3646  for(unsigned short i=0; i<(nInt*NPad); ++i)
3647  sources[i] = 0.0;
3648  }
3649 
3650  /*--- Loop over the chunk of elements and its integration points. ---*/
3651  for(unsigned short ll=0; ll<llEnd; ++ll) {
3652  const unsigned short llNVar = ll*nVar;
3653  const unsigned long lInd = l + ll;
3654  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
3655  const unsigned short iNPad = i*NPad;
3656 
3657  /* Determine the integration weight multiplied by the Jacobian. */
3658  const su2double *metricTerms = volElem[lInd].metricTerms.data()
3659  + i*nMetricPerPoint;
3660  const su2double weightJac = weights[i]*metricTerms[0];
3661 
3662  /* Set the pointer to the coordinates in this integration point and
3663  call the function to compute the source terms for the manufactured
3664  solution. */
3665  const su2double *coor = volElem[lInd].coorIntegrationPoints.data() + i*nDim;
3666 
3667  su2double sourceMan[5];
3668 
3669  VerificationSolution->GetMMSSourceTerm(coor, time, sourceMan);
3670 
3671  /*--- Subtract the source term of the manufactured solution, multiplied
3672  by the appropriate weight, from the possibly earlier computed
3673  source term. It is subtracted in order to be consistent with
3674  the definition of the residual used in this code. ---*/
3675  su2double *source = sources + iNPad + llNVar;
3676  for(unsigned short k=0; k<nVar; ++k)
3677  source[k] -= weightJac*sourceMan[k];
3678  }
3679  }
3680  }
3681  }
3682 
3683  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3684  /*--- Step 3: Compute the contribution to the residuals from the ---*/
3685  /*--- integration over the volume element. ---*/
3686  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3687 
3688  /* Call the general function to carry out the matrix product.
3689  Use solDOFs as a temporary storage for the matrix product. */
3690  blasFunctions->gemm(nDOFs, NPad, nInt*nDim, matDerBasisIntTrans, fluxes, solDOFs, config);
3691 
3692  /* Add the contribution from the source terms, if needed. Use solAndGradInt
3693  as temporary storage for the matrix product. */
3694  if( addSourceTerms ) {
3695 
3696  /* Call the general function to carry out the matrix product. */
3697  blasFunctions->gemm(nDOFs, NPad, nInt, matBasisIntTrans, sources, solAndGradInt, config);
3698 
3699  /* Add the residuals due to source terms to the volume residuals */
3700  for(unsigned short i=0; i<(nDOFs*NPad); ++i)
3701  solDOFs[i] += solAndGradInt[i];
3702  }
3703 
3704  /* Loop over the elements in this chunk to store the residuals
3705  in the appropriate locations. */
3706  for(unsigned short ll=0; ll<llEnd; ++ll) {
3707  const unsigned short llNVar = ll*nVar;
3708  const unsigned long lInd = l + ll;
3709 
3710  /* Easier storage of the residuals for this volume element. */
3711  su2double *res = VecResDOFs.data() + nVar*volElem[lInd].offsetDOFsSolLocal;
3712 
3713  /* Loop over the DOFs and copy the data. */
3714  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFs; ++i)
3715  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
3716  res[i*nVar+mm] = solDOFs[i*NPad+llNVar+mm];
3717  }
3718 
3719  /* Update the value of the counter l to the end index of the
3720  current chunk. */
3721  l = lEnd;
3722  }
3723 }
3724 
3725 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::ResidualFaces(CConfig *config,
3726  const unsigned long indFaceBeg,
3727  const unsigned long indFaceEnd,
3728  unsigned long &indResFaces,
3729  CNumerics *numerics,
3730  su2double *workArray) {
3731 
3732  /* Determine the number of faces that are treated simultaneously
3733  in the matrix products to obtain good gemm performance. */
3734  const unsigned short nPadInput = config->GetSizeMatMulPadding();
3735  const unsigned short nFaceSimul = nPadInput/nVar;
3736 
3737  /* Determine the minimum padded size in the matrix multiplications, which
3738  corresponds to 64 byte alignment. */
3739  const unsigned short nPadMin = 64/sizeof(passivedouble);
3740 
3741  /*--- Loop over the requested range of matching faces. Multiple faces
3742  are treated simultaneously to improve the performance of the matrix
3743  multiplications. As a consequence, the update of the counter l
3744  happens at the end of this loop section. ---*/
3745  for(unsigned long l=indFaceBeg; l<indFaceEnd;) {
3746 
3747  /* Determine the end index for this chunk of faces and the padded
3748  N value in the gemm computations. */
3749  unsigned long lEnd;
3750  unsigned short ind, llEnd, NPad;
3751 
3752  MetaDataChunkOfElem(matchingInternalFaces, l, indFaceEnd, nFaceSimul,
3753  nPadMin, lEnd, ind, llEnd, NPad);
3754 
3755  /* Get the necessary data from the standard face. */
3756  const unsigned short nInt = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetNIntegration();
3757  const su2double *weights = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetWeightsIntegration();
3758 
3759  const unsigned short nDOFsFace0 = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetNDOFsFaceSide0();
3760  const unsigned short nDOFsFace1 = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetNDOFsFaceSide1();
3761 
3762  const unsigned short nDOFsElem0 = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetNDOFsElemSide0();
3763  const unsigned short nDOFsElem1 = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetNDOFsElemSide1();
3764 
3765  /*--- Set the pointers for the local arrays. ---*/
3766  unsigned int sizeFluxes = nInt*nDim;
3767  sizeFluxes = NPad*max(sizeFluxes, (unsigned int) max(nDOFsElem0, nDOFsElem1));
3768 
3769  const unsigned int sizeGradSolInt = nInt*nDim*NPad;
3770 
3771  su2double *solIntL = workArray;
3772  su2double *solIntR = solIntL + NPad*max(nInt, nDOFsElem0);
3773  su2double *viscosityIntL = solIntR + NPad*max(nInt, nDOFsElem1);
3774  su2double *kOverCvIntL = viscosityIntL + llEnd*nInt;
3775  su2double *viscosityIntR = kOverCvIntL + llEnd*nInt;
3776  su2double *kOverCvIntR = viscosityIntR + llEnd*nInt;
3777  su2double *gradSolInt = kOverCvIntR + llEnd*nInt;
3778  su2double *fluxes = gradSolInt + sizeGradSolInt;
3779  su2double *viscFluxes = fluxes + sizeFluxes;
3780 
3781  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3782  /*--- Step 1: Compute the inviscid fluxes in the integration points of ---*/
3783  /*--- this chunk of matching faces. ---*/
3784  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3785 
3786  InviscidFluxesInternalMatchingFace(config, l, lEnd, NPad,
3787  solIntL, solIntR, fluxes, numerics);
3788 
3789  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3790  /*--- Step 2: Compute the viscous fluxes in the integration points of ---*/
3791  /*--- this chunk of matching faces and subtract them from the ---*/
3792  /*--- already computed inviscid fluxes. ---*/
3793  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3794 
3795  /*---------------------------*/
3796  /*--- Side 0 of the face. ---*/
3797  /*---------------------------*/
3798 
3799  /* Get the matrix, which contains the derivatives w.r.t. the
3800  parametric coordinates of the basis functions. */
3801  const su2double *derBasisElem = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetMatDerBasisElemIntegrationSide0();
3802 
3803  /* Set the pointer solElem to viscFluxes. This is just for readability,
3804  as the same memory can be used for the storage of the solution of the
3805  DOFs of the element and the viscous fluxes to be computed. */
3806  su2double *solElem = viscFluxes;
3807 
3808  /*--- Loop over the faces in this chunk to set the conserved variables
3809  in the DOFs of the faces. */
3810  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
3811  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
3812  const unsigned short llNVar = llRel*nVar;
3813 
3814  /* Determine the time level of the face, which is the minimum
3815  of the levels of the adjacent elements. */
3816  const unsigned long elemID0 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID0;
3817  const unsigned long elemID1 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID1;
3818  const unsigned short timeLevelFace = min(volElem[elemID0].timeLevel,
3819  volElem[elemID1].timeLevel);
3820 
3821  /* Determine the offset that must be applied to access the correct data
3822  for this elemID0 in the working vector of the solution. If the element
3823  has the same time level as the face offsetDOFsSolThisTimeLevel is used,
3824  otherwise offsetDOFsSolPrevTimeLevel is the correct value. */
3825  unsigned long offset;
3826  if(volElem[elemID0].timeLevel == timeLevelFace) {
3827  offset = volElem[elemID0].offsetDOFsSolLocal
3828  - volElem[elemID0].offsetDOFsSolThisTimeLevel;
3829  }
3830  else {
3831  offset = volElem[elemID0].offsetDOFsSolLocal
3832  - volElem[elemID0].offsetDOFsSolPrevTimeLevel;
3833  }
3834 
3835  /*--- Store the solution of the DOFs of the elemID0 in the correct
3836  sequence, such that a generalized approach is possible. ---*/
3837  const unsigned long *DOFsElem = matchingInternalFaces[ll].DOFsSolElementSide0.data();
3838  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFsElem0; ++i) {
3839  const su2double *solDOF = VecWorkSolDOFs[timeLevelFace].data()
3840  + nVar*(DOFsElem[i] - offset);
3841  su2double *sol = solElem + NPad*i + llNVar;
3842  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
3843  sol[mm] = solDOF[mm];
3844  }
3845  }
3846 
3847  /* Compute the gradients w.r.t. the parametric coordinates in the integration
3848  points. Call the general function to carry out the matrix product. */
3849  blasFunctions->gemm(nInt*nDim, NPad, nDOFsElem0, derBasisElem, solElem, gradSolInt, config);
3850 
3851  /*--- Loop over the faces in this chunk to compute the viscous flux
3852  vector for side 0. */
3853  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
3854 
3855  /* Determine the ID of the adjacent element. */
3856  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
3857  const unsigned long elemID0 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID0;
3858 
3859  /* Call the general function to compute the viscous flux in normal
3860  direction for side 0. */
3861  ViscousNormalFluxFace(&volElem[elemID0], llRel, nInt, NPad,
3862  0.0, false, solIntL, gradSolInt,
3863  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricCoorDerivFace0.data(),
3864  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricNormalsFace.data(),
3865  matchingInternalFaces[ll].wallDistance.data(),
3866  viscFluxes, viscosityIntL, kOverCvIntL);
3867  }
3868 
3869  /*--- Subtract half of the viscous fluxes from the inviscid fluxes. The
3870  factor 0.5 comes from the fact that the average of the viscous fluxes
3871  of side 0 and side 1 must be taken in the DG-FEM formulation. ---*/
3872  for(unsigned short j=0; j<(NPad*nInt); ++j) fluxes[j] -= 0.5*viscFluxes[j];
3873 
3874  /*---------------------------*/
3875  /*--- Side 1 of the face. ---*/
3876  /*---------------------------*/
3877 
3878  /* Get the matrix, which contains the derivatives w.r.t. the
3879  parametric coordinates of the basis functions. */
3880  derBasisElem = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetMatDerBasisElemIntegrationSide1();
3881 
3882  /*--- Loop over the faces in this chunk to set the conserved variables
3883  in the DOFs of the faces. */
3884  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
3885  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
3886  const unsigned short llNVar = llRel*nVar;
3887 
3888  /* Determine the time level of the face, which is the minimum
3889  of the levels of the adjacent elements. */
3890  const unsigned long elemID0 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID0;
3891  const unsigned long elemID1 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID1;
3892  const unsigned short timeLevelFace = min(volElem[elemID0].timeLevel,
3893  volElem[elemID1].timeLevel);
3894 
3895  /* Determine the offset that must be applied to access the correct data
3896  for this elemID0 in the working vector of the solution. If the element
3897  has the same time level as the face offsetDOFsSolThisTimeLevel is used,
3898  otherwise offsetDOFsSolPrevTimeLevel is the correct value. */
3899  unsigned long offset;
3900  if(volElem[elemID1].timeLevel == timeLevelFace) {
3901  offset = volElem[elemID1].offsetDOFsSolLocal
3902  - volElem[elemID1].offsetDOFsSolThisTimeLevel;
3903  }
3904  else {
3905  offset = volElem[elemID1].offsetDOFsSolLocal
3906  - volElem[elemID1].offsetDOFsSolPrevTimeLevel;
3907  }
3908 
3909  /*--- Store the solution of the DOFs of the elemID1 in the correct
3910  sequence, such that a generalized approach is possible. ---*/
3911  const unsigned long *DOFsElem = matchingInternalFaces[ll].DOFsSolElementSide1.data();
3912  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFsElem1; ++i) {
3913  const su2double *solDOF = VecWorkSolDOFs[timeLevelFace].data()
3914  + nVar*(DOFsElem[i] - offset);
3915  su2double *sol = solElem + NPad*i + llNVar;
3916  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
3917  sol[mm] = solDOF[mm];
3918  }
3919  }
3920 
3921  /* Compute the gradients w.r.t. the parametric coordinates in the integration
3922  points. Call the general function to carry out the matrix product. */
3923  blasFunctions->gemm(nInt*nDim, NPad, nDOFsElem1, derBasisElem, solElem, gradSolInt, config);
3924 
3925  /*--- Loop over the faces in this chunk to compute the viscous flux
3926  vector for side 1. */
3927  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
3928 
3929  /* Determine the ID of the adjacent element. */
3930  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
3931  const unsigned long elemID1 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID1;
3932 
3933  /* Call the general function to compute the viscous flux in normal
3934  direction for side 1. */
3935  ViscousNormalFluxFace(&volElem[elemID1], llRel, nInt, NPad,
3936  0.0, false, solIntR, gradSolInt,
3937  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricCoorDerivFace1.data(),
3938  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricNormalsFace.data(),
3939  matchingInternalFaces[ll].wallDistance.data(),
3940  viscFluxes, viscosityIntR, kOverCvIntR);
3941  }
3942 
3943  /*--- Subtract half of the viscous fluxes from the inviscid fluxes. ---*/
3944  for(unsigned short j=0; j<(NPad*nInt); ++j) fluxes[j] -= 0.5*viscFluxes[j];
3945 
3946  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3947  /*--- Step 3: Compute the penalty terms in the integration points of ---*/
3948  /*--- this chunk of matching faces and add them to the already ---*/
3949  /*--- stored inviscid and viscous fluxes. ---*/
3950  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3951 
3952  /* Get the required constant needed for the penalty terms. */
3953  const su2double ConstPenFace = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetPenaltyConstant();
3954 
3955  /*--- Loop over the faces in this chunk to compute the penalty fluxes. ---*/
3956  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
3957 
3958  /* Get the length scales of the adjacent elements. */
3959  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
3960  const unsigned long elemID0 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID0;
3961  const unsigned long elemID1 = matchingInternalFaces[ll].elemID1;
3962 
3963  const su2double lenScale0 = volElem[elemID0].lenScale;
3964  const su2double lenScale1 = volElem[elemID1].lenScale;
3965 
3966  /* Call the function PenaltyTermsFluxFace to compute the actual penalty
3967  terms. Use the array viscFluxes as storage. */
3968  PenaltyTermsFluxFace(llRel, nInt, NPad, solIntL, solIntR, viscosityIntL,
3969  viscosityIntR, kOverCvIntL, kOverCvIntR,
3970  ConstPenFace, lenScale0, lenScale1,
3971  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricNormalsFace.data(),
3972  viscFluxes);
3973  }
3974 
3975  /* Add the penalty fluxes to the earlier computed fluxes. */
3976  for(unsigned short j=0; j<(NPad*nInt); ++j) fluxes[j] += viscFluxes[j];
3977 
3978  /* Multiply the fluxes with the integration weight of the corresponding
3979  integration point. */
3980  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
3981  su2double *flux = fluxes + i*NPad;
3982 
3983  for(unsigned short j=0; j<NPad; ++j)
3984  flux[j] *= weights[i];
3985  }
3986 
3987  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3988  /*--- Step 4: Compute the contribution to the residuals from the ---*/
3989  /*--- integration over this internal matching face. ---*/
3990  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
3991 
3992  /* Set the value of the offset of the residual between each of the fused
3993  faces. This depends whether or not symmetrizing terms are stored.
3994  Also set the location where the symmetrizing terms of the first face
3995  must be stored. */
3996  unsigned long offsetRes = nDOFsFace0 + nDOFsFace1;
3997  if( symmetrizingTermsPresent ) offsetRes += nDOFsElem0 + nDOFsElem1;
3998 
3999  unsigned long indResSym = indResFaces + nDOFsFace0 + nDOFsFace1;
4000 
4001  /* Get the correct form of the basis functions needed for the matrix
4002  multiplication to compute the residual. Use gradSolInt as a temporary
4003  buffer to store this product. */
4004  const su2double *basisFaceTrans = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetBasisFaceIntegrationTransposeSide0();
4005  su2double *resSide0 = gradSolInt;
4006 
4007  /* Call the general function to carry out the matrix product. */
4008  blasFunctions->gemm(nDOFsFace0, NPad, nInt, basisFaceTrans, fluxes, resSide0, config);
4009 
4010  /* Check if the number of DOFs on both sides of the face is different.
4011  In that case also the matrix product with the basis functions on side 1
4012  must be carried out. Use viscFluxes as a temporary buffer to store
4013  this product. */
4014  su2double *resSide1 = viscFluxes;
4015  if(nDOFsFace1 != nDOFsFace0) {
4016  basisFaceTrans = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetBasisFaceIntegrationTransposeSide1();
4017  blasFunctions->gemm(nDOFsFace1, NPad, nInt, basisFaceTrans, fluxes, resSide1, config);
4018  }
4019 
4020  /* Loop over the number of faces in this chunk. */
4021  for(unsigned short ll=0; ll<llEnd; ++ll) {
4022  const unsigned short llNVar = ll*nVar;
4023 
4024  /* Set the pointer in the residual array where the residual of side 0
4025  and side 1 of this face must be stored. Update the counter. */
4026  su2double *resFace0 = VecResFaces.data() + indResFaces*nVar;
4027  su2double *resFace1 = VecResFaces.data() + (indResFaces+nDOFsFace0)*nVar;
4028  indResFaces += offsetRes;
4029 
4030  /* Loop over the DOFs and copy the data for side 0. */
4031  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFsFace0; ++i)
4032  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
4033  resFace0[nVar*i+mm] = resSide0[NPad*i+llNVar+mm];
4034 
4035  /* If the number of DOFs on both sides is the same, then the residual
4036  of side 1 is obtained by simply negating the residual of side 0.
4037  Otherwise a copy must be carried out and the residual negated,
4038  because the normal is pointing into the adjacent element for side 1. */
4039  if(nDOFsFace1 == nDOFsFace0) {
4040  for(unsigned short i=0; i<(nVar*nDOFsFace1); ++i)
4041  resFace1[i] = -resFace0[i];
4042  }
4043  else {
4044  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFsFace1; ++i)
4045  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
4046  resFace1[nVar*i+mm] = -resSide1[NPad*i+llNVar+mm];
4047  }
4048  }
4049 
4050  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4051  /*--- Step 5: Compute and distribute the symmetrizing terms, if ---*/
4052  /*--- present. Note that these terms must be distributed to ---*/
4053  /*--- DOFs of the adjacent element, not only of the face. ---*/
4054  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4055 
4056  if( symmetrizingTermsPresent ) {
4057 
4058  /* Use gradSolInt as a buffer to store the parametric fluxes. */
4059  su2double *paramFluxes = gradSolInt;
4060 
4061  /* The symmetrizing fluxes will be multiplied by 0.5 times the theta
4062  parameter. Store this factor a bit easier. */
4063  const su2double halfTheta = 0.5*config->GetTheta_Interior_Penalty_DGFEM();
4064 
4065  /* Loop over the faces in this chunk to compute the symmetrizing fluxes. */
4066  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
4067 
4068  /* Compute the symmetrizing fluxes in the nDim directions in the
4069  integration points of the face. */
4070  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
4071  SymmetrizingFluxesFace(llRel, nInt, NPad, solIntL, solIntR, viscosityIntL,
4072  viscosityIntR, kOverCvIntL, kOverCvIntR,
4073  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricNormalsFace.data(),
4074  fluxes);
4075 
4076  /* Transform the fluxes, such that they must be multiplied with the
4077  gradients w.r.t. the parametric coordinates rather than the
4078  Cartesian coordinates of the basis functions. Also a multiplication
4079  with the integration weight and the theta parameter is carried out.
4080  In this loop only side 0 of the face is treated. */
4081  TransformSymmetrizingFluxes(llRel, nInt, NPad, halfTheta, fluxes, weights,
4082  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricCoorDerivFace0.data(),
4083  paramFluxes);
4084  }
4085 
4086  /* Call the general function to carry out the matrix product to compute
4087  the residual for side 0. Use solIntL as storage for the residual. */
4088  const su2double *derBasisElemTrans = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetMatDerBasisElemIntegrationTransposeSide0();
4089  blasFunctions->gemm(nDOFsElem0, NPad, nInt*nDim, derBasisElemTrans, paramFluxes, solIntL, config);
4090 
4091  /* Loop over the faces in this chunk to compute the transformed
4092  symmetrizing fluxes for side 1. */
4093  for(unsigned long ll=l; ll<lEnd; ++ll) {
4094  const unsigned short llRel = ll - l;
4095  TransformSymmetrizingFluxes(llRel, nInt, NPad, halfTheta, fluxes, weights,
4096  matchingInternalFaces[ll].metricCoorDerivFace1.data(),
4097  paramFluxes);
4098  }
4099 
4100  /* Call the general function to carry out the matrix product to compute
4101  the residual for side 1. Note that the symmetrizing residual should not
4102  be negated, because two minus signs enter the formulation for side 1,
4103  which cancel each other. Use solIntR as storage for the residual. */
4104  derBasisElemTrans = standardMatchingFacesSol[ind].GetMatDerBasisElemIntegrationTransposeSide1();
4105  blasFunctions->gemm(nDOFsElem1, NPad, nInt*nDim, derBasisElemTrans, paramFluxes, solIntR, config);
4106 
4107  /* Loop over the number of faces in this chunk. */
4108  for(unsigned short ll=0; ll<llEnd; ++ll) {
4109  const unsigned short llNVar = ll*nVar;
4110 
4111  /* Set the pointer in the residual array where the residual of side 0
4112  and side 1 of this face must be stored. Update the counter. */
4113  su2double *resElem0 = VecResFaces.data() + indResSym*nVar;
4114  su2double *resElem1 = VecResFaces.data() + (indResSym+nDOFsElem0)*nVar;
4115  indResSym += offsetRes;
4116 
4117  /* Loop over the DOFs of the element and copy the data for side 0. */
4118  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFsElem0; ++i)
4119  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
4120  resElem0[nVar*i+mm] = solIntL[NPad*i+llNVar+mm];
4121 
4122  /* Loop over the DOFs of the element and copy the data for side 1. */
4123  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nDOFsElem1; ++i)
4124  for(unsigned short mm=0; mm<nVar; ++mm)
4125  resElem1[nVar*i+mm] = solIntR[NPad*i+llNVar+mm];
4126  }
4127  }
4128 
4129  /* Update the value of the counter l to the end index of the
4130  current chunk. */
4131  l = lEnd;
4132  }
4133 }
4134 
4135 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::ViscousNormalFluxFace(const CVolumeElementFEM *adjVolElem,
4136  const unsigned short indFaceChunk,
4137  const unsigned short nInt,
4138  const unsigned short NPad,
4139  const su2double Wall_HeatFlux,
4140  const bool HeatFlux_Prescribed,
4141  const su2double *solInt,
4142  const su2double *gradSolInt,
4143  const su2double *metricCoorDerivFace,
4144  const su2double *metricNormalsFace,
4145  const su2double *wallDistanceInt,
4146  su2double *viscNormFluxes,
4147  su2double *viscosityInt,
4148  su2double *kOverCvInt) {
4149 
4150  /* Multiplication factor for the heat flux. It is set to zero if the wall heat flux
4151  is prescribed, such that the computed heat flux is zero, and to one otherwise. */
4152  const su2double factHeatFlux = HeatFlux_Prescribed ? su2double(0.0): su2double(1.0);
4153 
4154  /* Set the value of the prescribed heat flux for the same reason. */
4155  const su2double HeatFlux = HeatFlux_Prescribed ? Wall_HeatFlux : su2double(0.0);
4156 
4157  /* Compute the length scale for the LES of the adjacent element. */
4158  const unsigned short iind = adjVolElem->indStandardElement;
4159  unsigned short nPoly = standardElementsSol[iind].GetNPoly();
4160  if(nPoly == 0) nPoly = 1;
4161 
4162  const su2double lenScale_LES = adjVolElem->lenScale/nPoly;
4163 
4164  /* Determine the offset between r- and -s-derivatives, which is also the
4165  offset between s- and t-derivatives. */
4166  const unsigned short offDeriv = NPad*nInt;
4167 
4168  /* Make a distinction between two and three space dimensions
4169  in order to have the most efficient code. */
4170  switch( nDim ) {
4171 
4172  case 2: {
4173 
4174  /* 2D simulation. Loop over the integration points to
4175  compute the viscous fluxes. */
4176  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4177 
4178  /* Easier storage of the metric terms needed to compute the Cartesian
4179  gradients in this integration point and the starting locations of
4180  the solution and the gradients, w.r.t. the parametric coordinates
4181  of this solution. */
4182  const unsigned short offPointer = NPad*i + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4183  const su2double *metricTerms = metricCoorDerivFace + i*nDim*nDim;
4184  const su2double *sol = solInt + offPointer;
4185  const su2double *dSolDr = gradSolInt + offPointer;
4186  const su2double *dSolDs = dSolDr + offDeriv;
4187 
4188  /* Easier storage of the metric terms in this integration point. */
4189  const su2double drdx = metricTerms[0];
4190  const su2double drdy = metricTerms[1];
4191 
4192  const su2double dsdx = metricTerms[2];
4193  const su2double dsdy = metricTerms[3];
4194 
4195  /*--- Compute the Cartesian gradients of the solution. ---*/
4196  su2double solGradCart[4][2];
4197 
4198  solGradCart[0][0] = dSolDr[0]*drdx + dSolDs[0]*dsdx;
4199  solGradCart[1][0] = dSolDr[1]*drdx + dSolDs[1]*dsdx;
4200  solGradCart[2][0] = dSolDr[2]*drdx + dSolDs[2]*dsdx;
4201  solGradCart[3][0] = dSolDr[3]*drdx + dSolDs[3]*dsdx;
4202 
4203  solGradCart[0][1] = dSolDr[0]*drdy + dSolDs[0]*dsdy;
4204  solGradCart[1][1] = dSolDr[1]*drdy + dSolDs[1]*dsdy;
4205  solGradCart[2][1] = dSolDr[2]*drdy + dSolDs[2]*dsdy;
4206  solGradCart[3][1] = dSolDr[3]*drdy + dSolDs[3]*dsdy;
4207 
4208  /*--- Call the function ViscousNormalFluxIntegrationPoint to compute the
4209  actual normal viscous flux. The viscosity and thermal conductivity
4210  are stored for later use. ---*/
4211  const su2double *normal = metricNormalsFace + i*(nDim+1);
4212  su2double *normalFlux = viscNormFluxes + offPointer;
4213  const su2double wallDist = wallDistanceInt ? wallDistanceInt[i] : 0.0;
4214 
4215  su2double Viscosity, kOverCv;
4216 
4217  ViscousNormalFluxIntegrationPoint_2D(sol, solGradCart, normal, HeatFlux,
4218  factHeatFlux, wallDist, lenScale_LES,
4219  Viscosity, kOverCv, normalFlux);
4220 
4221  const unsigned short ind = indFaceChunk*nInt + i;
4222  viscosityInt[ind] = Viscosity;
4223  kOverCvInt[ind] = kOverCv;
4224  }
4225 
4226  break;
4227  }
4228 
4229  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4230 
4231  case 3: {
4232 
4233  /* 3D simulation. Loop over the integration points to
4234  compute the viscous fluxes. */
4235  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4236 
4237  /* Easier storage of the metric terms needed to compute the Cartesian
4238  gradients in this integration point and the starting locations of
4239  the solution and the gradients, w.r.t. the parametric coordinates
4240  of this solution. */
4241  const unsigned short offPointer = NPad*i + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4242  const su2double *metricTerms = metricCoorDerivFace + i*nDim*nDim;
4243  const su2double *sol = solInt + offPointer;
4244  const su2double *dSolDr = gradSolInt + offPointer;
4245  const su2double *dSolDs = dSolDr + offDeriv;
4246  const su2double *dSolDt = dSolDs + offDeriv;
4247 
4248  /* Easier storage of the metric terms in this integration point. */
4249  const su2double drdx = metricTerms[0];
4250  const su2double drdy = metricTerms[1];
4251  const su2double drdz = metricTerms[2];
4252 
4253  const su2double dsdx = metricTerms[3];
4254  const su2double dsdy = metricTerms[4];
4255  const su2double dsdz = metricTerms[5];
4256 
4257  const su2double dtdx = metricTerms[6];
4258  const su2double dtdy = metricTerms[7];
4259  const su2double dtdz = metricTerms[8];
4260 
4261  /*--- Compute the Cartesian gradients of the solution. ---*/
4262  su2double solGradCart[5][3];
4263 
4264  solGradCart[0][0] = dSolDr[0]*drdx + dSolDs[0]*dsdx + dSolDt[0]*dtdx;
4265  solGradCart[1][0] = dSolDr[1]*drdx + dSolDs[1]*dsdx + dSolDt[1]*dtdx;
4266  solGradCart[2][0] = dSolDr[2]*drdx + dSolDs[2]*dsdx + dSolDt[2]*dtdx;
4267  solGradCart[3][0] = dSolDr[3]*drdx + dSolDs[3]*dsdx + dSolDt[3]*dtdx;
4268  solGradCart[4][0] = dSolDr[4]*drdx + dSolDs[4]*dsdx + dSolDt[4]*dtdx;
4269 
4270  solGradCart[0][1] = dSolDr[0]*drdy + dSolDs[0]*dsdy + dSolDt[0]*dtdy;
4271  solGradCart[1][1] = dSolDr[1]*drdy + dSolDs[1]*dsdy + dSolDt[1]*dtdy;
4272  solGradCart[2][1] = dSolDr[2]*drdy + dSolDs[2]*dsdy + dSolDt[2]*dtdy;
4273  solGradCart[3][1] = dSolDr[3]*drdy + dSolDs[3]*dsdy + dSolDt[3]*dtdy;
4274  solGradCart[4][1] = dSolDr[4]*drdy + dSolDs[4]*dsdy + dSolDt[4]*dtdy;
4275 
4276  solGradCart[0][2] = dSolDr[0]*drdz + dSolDs[0]*dsdz + dSolDt[0]*dtdz;
4277  solGradCart[1][2] = dSolDr[1]*drdz + dSolDs[1]*dsdz + dSolDt[1]*dtdz;
4278  solGradCart[2][2] = dSolDr[2]*drdz + dSolDs[2]*dsdz + dSolDt[2]*dtdz;
4279  solGradCart[3][2] = dSolDr[3]*drdz + dSolDs[3]*dsdz + dSolDt[3]*dtdz;
4280  solGradCart[4][2] = dSolDr[4]*drdz + dSolDs[4]*dsdz + dSolDt[4]*dtdz;
4281 
4282  /*--- Call the function ViscousNormalFluxIntegrationPoint to compute the
4283  actual normal viscous flux. The viscosity and thermal conductivity
4284  are stored for later use. ---*/
4285  const su2double *normal = metricNormalsFace + i*(nDim+1);
4286  su2double *normalFlux = viscNormFluxes + offPointer;
4287  const su2double wallDist = wallDistanceInt ? wallDistanceInt[i] : 0.0;
4288 
4289  su2double Viscosity, kOverCv;
4290 
4291  ViscousNormalFluxIntegrationPoint_3D(sol, solGradCart, normal, HeatFlux,
4292  factHeatFlux, wallDist, lenScale_LES,
4293  Viscosity, kOverCv, normalFlux);
4294 
4295  const unsigned short ind = indFaceChunk*nInt + i;
4296  viscosityInt[ind] = Viscosity;
4297  kOverCvInt[ind] = kOverCv;
4298  }
4299 
4300  break;
4301  }
4302  }
4303 }
4304 
4305 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::ViscousNormalFluxIntegrationPoint_2D(const su2double *sol,
4306  const su2double solGradCart[4][2],
4307  const su2double *normal,
4308  const su2double HeatFlux,
4309  const su2double factHeatFlux,
4310  const su2double wallDist,
4311  const su2double lenScale_LES,
4312  su2double &Viscosity,
4313  su2double &kOverCv,
4314  su2double *normalFlux) {
4315 
4316  /* Constant factor present in the heat flux vector, namely the ratio of
4317  thermal conductivity and viscosity. */
4318  const su2double factHeatFlux_Lam = Gamma/Prandtl_Lam;
4319  const su2double factHeatFlux_Turb = Gamma/Prandtl_Turb;
4320 
4321  /*--- Compute the velocities and static energy in this integration point. ---*/
4322  const su2double rhoInv = 1.0/sol[0];
4323  const su2double u = rhoInv*sol[1];
4324  const su2double v = rhoInv*sol[2];
4325 
4326  const su2double TotalEnergy = rhoInv*sol[3];
4327  const su2double StaticEnergy = TotalEnergy - 0.5*(u*u + v*v);
4328 
4329  /*--- Compute the Cartesian gradients of the velocities and static energy
4330  in this integration point and also the divergence of the velocity. ---*/
4331  const su2double dudx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[1][0] - u*solGradCart[0][0]);
4332  const su2double dudy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[1][1] - u*solGradCart[0][1]);
4333 
4334  const su2double dvdx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[2][0] - v*solGradCart[0][0]);
4335  const su2double dvdy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[2][1] - v*solGradCart[0][1]);
4336 
4337  const su2double dStaticEnergyDx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[3][0]
4338  - TotalEnergy*solGradCart[0][0])
4339  - u*dudx - v*dvdx;
4340  const su2double dStaticEnergyDy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[3][1]
4341  - TotalEnergy*solGradCart[0][1])
4342  - u*dudy - v*dvdy;
4343 
4344  const su2double divVel = dudx + dvdy;
4345 
4346  /*--- Compute the laminar viscosity. ---*/
4347  FluidModel->SetTDState_rhoe(sol[0], StaticEnergy);
4348  const su2double ViscosityLam = FluidModel->GetLaminarViscosity();
4349 
4350  /*--- Compute the eddy viscosity, if needed. ---*/
4351  su2double ViscosityTurb = 0.0;
4352  if( SGSModelUsed )
4353  ViscosityTurb = SGSModel->ComputeEddyViscosity_2D(sol[0], dudx, dudy, dvdx,
4354  dvdy, lenScale_LES, wallDist);
4355 
4356  /* Compute the total viscosity and heat conductivity. Note that the heat
4357  conductivity is divided by the Cv, because gradients of internal energy
4358  are computed and not temperature. */
4359  Viscosity = ViscosityLam + ViscosityTurb;
4360  kOverCv = ViscosityLam*factHeatFlux_Lam + ViscosityTurb*factHeatFlux_Turb;
4361 
4362  /*--- Set the value of the second viscosity and compute the divergence
4363  term in the viscous normal stresses. ---*/
4364  const su2double lambda = -TWO3*Viscosity;
4365  const su2double lamDivTerm = lambda*divVel;
4366 
4367  /*--- Compute the viscous stress tensor and minus the heatflux vector.
4368  The heat flux vector is multiplied by factHeatFlux, such that the
4369  case of a prescribed heat flux is treated correctly. ---*/
4370  const su2double tauxx = 2.0*Viscosity*dudx + lamDivTerm;
4371  const su2double tauyy = 2.0*Viscosity*dvdy + lamDivTerm;
4372  const su2double tauxy = Viscosity*(dudy + dvdx);
4373 
4374  const su2double qx = factHeatFlux*kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDx;
4375  const su2double qy = factHeatFlux*kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDy;
4376 
4377  /* Compute the unscaled normal vector. */
4378  const su2double nx = normal[0]*normal[2];
4379  const su2double ny = normal[1]*normal[2];
4380 
4381  /*--- Compute the viscous normal flux. Note that the energy flux get a
4382  contribution from both the prescribed and the computed heat flux.
4383  At least one of these terms is zero. ---*/
4384  normalFlux[0] = 0.0;
4385  normalFlux[1] = tauxx*nx + tauxy*ny;
4386  normalFlux[2] = tauxy*nx + tauyy*ny;
4387  normalFlux[3] = normal[2]*HeatFlux
4388  + (u*tauxx + v*tauxy + qx)*nx + (u*tauxy + v*tauyy + qy)*ny;
4389 }
4390 
4391 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::ViscousNormalFluxIntegrationPoint_3D(const su2double *sol,
4392  const su2double solGradCart[5][3],
4393  const su2double *normal,
4394  const su2double HeatFlux,
4395  const su2double factHeatFlux,
4396  const su2double wallDist,
4397  const su2double lenScale_LES,
4398  su2double &Viscosity,
4399  su2double &kOverCv,
4400  su2double *normalFlux) {
4401 
4402  /* Constant factor present in the heat flux vector, namely the ratio of
4403  thermal conductivity and viscosity. */
4404  const su2double factHeatFlux_Lam = Gamma/Prandtl_Lam;
4405  const su2double factHeatFlux_Turb = Gamma/Prandtl_Turb;
4406 
4407  /*--- Compute the velocities and static energy in this integration point. ---*/
4408  const su2double rhoInv = 1.0/sol[0];
4409  const su2double u = rhoInv*sol[1];
4410  const su2double v = rhoInv*sol[2];
4411  const su2double w = rhoInv*sol[3];
4412 
4413  const su2double TotalEnergy = rhoInv*sol[4];
4414  const su2double StaticEnergy = TotalEnergy - 0.5*(u*u + v*v + w*w);
4415 
4416  /*--- Compute the Cartesian gradients of the velocities and static energy
4417  in this integration point and also the divergence of the velocity. ---*/
4418  const su2double dudx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[1][0] - u*solGradCart[0][0]);
4419  const su2double dudy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[1][1] - u*solGradCart[0][1]);
4420  const su2double dudz = rhoInv*(solGradCart[1][2] - u*solGradCart[0][2]);
4421 
4422  const su2double dvdx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[2][0] - v*solGradCart[0][0]);
4423  const su2double dvdy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[2][1] - v*solGradCart[0][1]);
4424  const su2double dvdz = rhoInv*(solGradCart[2][2] - v*solGradCart[0][2]);
4425 
4426  const su2double dwdx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[3][0] - w*solGradCart[0][0]);
4427  const su2double dwdy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[3][1] - w*solGradCart[0][1]);
4428  const su2double dwdz = rhoInv*(solGradCart[3][2] - w*solGradCart[0][2]);
4429 
4430  const su2double dStaticEnergyDx = rhoInv*(solGradCart[4][0]
4431  - TotalEnergy*solGradCart[0][0])
4432  - u*dudx - v*dvdx - w*dwdx;
4433  const su2double dStaticEnergyDy = rhoInv*(solGradCart[4][1]
4434  - TotalEnergy*solGradCart[0][1])
4435  - u*dudy - v*dvdy - w*dwdy;
4436  const su2double dStaticEnergyDz = rhoInv*(solGradCart[4][2]
4437  - TotalEnergy*solGradCart[0][2])
4438  - u*dudz - v*dvdz - w*dwdz;
4439 
4440  const su2double divVel = dudx + dvdy + dwdz;
4441 
4442  /*--- Compute the laminar viscosity. ---*/
4443  FluidModel->SetTDState_rhoe(sol[0], StaticEnergy);
4444  const su2double ViscosityLam = FluidModel->GetLaminarViscosity();
4445 
4446  /*--- Compute the eddy viscosity, if needed. ---*/
4447  su2double ViscosityTurb = 0.0;
4448  if( SGSModelUsed )
4449  ViscosityTurb = SGSModel->ComputeEddyViscosity_3D(sol[0], dudx, dudy, dudz,
4450  dvdx, dvdy, dvdz, dwdx,
4451  dwdy, dwdz, lenScale_LES,
4452  wallDist);
4453 
4454  /* Compute the total viscosity and heat conductivity. Note that the heat
4455  conductivity is divided by the Cv, because gradients of internal energy
4456  are computed and not temperature. */
4457  Viscosity = ViscosityLam + ViscosityTurb;
4458  kOverCv = ViscosityLam*factHeatFlux_Lam + ViscosityTurb*factHeatFlux_Turb;
4459 
4460  /*--- Set the value of the second viscosity and compute the divergence
4461  term in the viscous normal stresses. ---*/
4462  const su2double lambda = -TWO3*Viscosity;
4463  const su2double lamDivTerm = lambda*divVel;
4464 
4465  /*--- Compute the viscous stress tensor and minus the heatflux vector.
4466  The heat flux vector is multiplied by factHeatFlux, such that the
4467  case of a prescribed heat flux is treated correctly. ---*/
4468  const su2double tauxx = 2.0*Viscosity*dudx + lamDivTerm;
4469  const su2double tauyy = 2.0*Viscosity*dvdy + lamDivTerm;
4470  const su2double tauzz = 2.0*Viscosity*dwdz + lamDivTerm;
4471 
4472  const su2double tauxy = Viscosity*(dudy + dvdx);
4473  const su2double tauxz = Viscosity*(dudz + dwdx);
4474  const su2double tauyz = Viscosity*(dvdz + dwdy);
4475 
4476  const su2double qx = factHeatFlux*kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDx;
4477  const su2double qy = factHeatFlux*kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDy;
4478  const su2double qz = factHeatFlux*kOverCv*dStaticEnergyDz;
4479 
4480  /* Compute the unscaled normal vector. */
4481  const su2double nx = normal[0]*normal[3];
4482  const su2double ny = normal[1]*normal[3];
4483  const su2double nz = normal[2]*normal[3];
4484 
4485  /*--- Compute the viscous normal flux. Note that the energy flux get a
4486  contribution from both the prescribed and the computed heat flux.
4487  At least one of these terms is zero. ---*/
4488  normalFlux[0] = 0.0;
4489  normalFlux[1] = tauxx*nx + tauxy*ny + tauxz*nz;
4490  normalFlux[2] = tauxy*nx + tauyy*ny + tauyz*nz;
4491  normalFlux[3] = tauxz*nx + tauyz*ny + tauzz*nz;
4492  normalFlux[4] = normal[3]*HeatFlux
4493  + (u*tauxx + v*tauxy + w*tauxz + qx)*nx
4494  + (u*tauxy + v*tauyy + w*tauyz + qy)*ny
4495  + (u*tauxz + v*tauyz + w*tauzz + qz)*nz;
4496 }
4497 
4498 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::PenaltyTermsFluxFace(const unsigned short indFaceChunk,
4499  const unsigned short nInt,
4500  const unsigned short NPad,
4501  const su2double *solInt0,
4502  const su2double *solInt1,
4503  const su2double *viscosityInt0,
4504  const su2double *viscosityInt1,
4505  const su2double *kOverCvInt0,
4506  const su2double *kOverCvInt1,
4507  const su2double ConstPenFace,
4508  const su2double lenScale0,
4509  const su2double lenScale1,
4510  const su2double *metricNormalsFace,
4511  su2double *penaltyFluxes) {
4512 
4513  /* Constant ratio of the second viscosity and the viscosity itself. */
4514  const su2double lambdaOverMu = -TWO3;
4515 
4516  /* The eigenvalues of the viscous Jacobian, scaled by the kinematic viscosity,
4517  are 1.0, 2.0 + lambdaOverMu and kOverCv/Mu. The last is variable due to the
4518  possible presence of an eddy viscosity, but the first two are constant and
4519  the maximum can be determined. */
4520  const su2double radOverNuTerm = max(1.0, 2.0+lambdaOverMu);
4521 
4522  /*--- Make a distinction between 2D and 3D for efficiency. ---*/
4523  switch ( nDim ) {
4524  case 2: {
4525 
4526  /* 2D simulation. Loop over the integration points to compute
4527  the penalty fluxes. */
4528  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4529 
4530  /* Easier storage of the variables for this integration point. */
4531  const unsigned short offPointer = NPad*i + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4532  const su2double *sol0 = solInt0 + offPointer;
4533  const su2double *sol1 = solInt1 + offPointer;
4534  const su2double *normal = metricNormalsFace + i*(nDim+1);
4535  su2double *flux = penaltyFluxes + offPointer;
4536 
4537  /* Determine the ratio of kOverCv and mu for both sides and compute the
4538  spectral radius of the viscous terms, scaled by kinematic viscosity. */
4539  const unsigned short ind = indFaceChunk*nInt + i;
4540  const su2double factHeatFlux0 = kOverCvInt0[ind]/viscosityInt0[ind];
4541  const su2double factHeatFlux1 = kOverCvInt1[ind]/viscosityInt1[ind];
4542 
4543  const su2double radOverNu0 = max(radOverNuTerm, factHeatFlux0);
4544  const su2double radOverNu1 = max(radOverNuTerm, factHeatFlux1);
4545 
4546  /* Compute the kinematic viscosities of both sides. Multiply it by
4547  ConstPenFace and divide by the length scale. */
4548  const su2double nu0 = ConstPenFace*viscosityInt0[ind]/(lenScale0*sol0[0]);
4549  const su2double nu1 = ConstPenFace*viscosityInt1[ind]/(lenScale1*sol1[0]);
4550 
4551  /* Compute the penalty parameter of this face as the maximum of the
4552  penalty parameter from both sides. Multiply by the area to obtain the
4553  correct expression. */
4554  const su2double pen0 = radOverNu0*nu0;
4555  const su2double pen1 = radOverNu1*nu1;
4556 
4557  const su2double penFace = normal[2]*max(pen0, pen1);
4558 
4559  /* Compute the penalty flux, where it is assumed that the normal points from
4560  side 0 to side 1. */
4561  flux[0] = penFace*(sol0[0] - sol1[0]);
4562  flux[1] = penFace*(sol0[1] - sol1[1]);
4563  flux[2] = penFace*(sol0[2] - sol1[2]);
4564  flux[3] = penFace*(sol0[3] - sol1[3]);
4565  }
4566 
4567  break;
4568  }
4569 
4570  /*----------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4571 
4572  case 3: {
4573 
4574  /* 3D simulation. Loop over the integration points to compute
4575  the penalty fluxes. */
4576  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4577 
4578  /* Easier storage of the variables for this integration point. */
4579  const unsigned short offPointer = NPad*i + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4580  const su2double *sol0 = solInt0 + offPointer;
4581  const su2double *sol1 = solInt1 + offPointer;
4582  const su2double *normal = metricNormalsFace + i*(nDim+1);
4583  su2double *flux = penaltyFluxes + offPointer;
4584 
4585  /* Determine the ratio of kOverCv and mu for both sides and compute the
4586  spectral radius of the viscous terms, scaled by kinematic viscosity. */
4587  const unsigned short ind = indFaceChunk*nInt + i;
4588  const su2double factHeatFlux0 = kOverCvInt0[ind]/viscosityInt0[ind];
4589  const su2double factHeatFlux1 = kOverCvInt1[ind]/viscosityInt1[ind];
4590 
4591  const su2double radOverNu0 = max(radOverNuTerm, factHeatFlux0);
4592  const su2double radOverNu1 = max(radOverNuTerm, factHeatFlux1);
4593 
4594  /* Compute the kinematic viscosities of both sides. Multiply it by
4595  ConstPenFace and divide by the length scale. */
4596  const su2double nu0 = ConstPenFace*viscosityInt0[ind]/(lenScale0*sol0[0]);
4597  const su2double nu1 = ConstPenFace*viscosityInt1[ind]/(lenScale1*sol1[0]);
4598 
4599  /* Compute the penalty parameter of this face as the maximum of the
4600  penalty parameter from both sides. Multiply by the area to obtain the
4601  correct expression. */
4602  const su2double pen0 = radOverNu0*nu0;
4603  const su2double pen1 = radOverNu1*nu1;
4604 
4605  const su2double penFace = normal[3]*max(pen0, pen1);
4606 
4607  /* Compute the penalty flux, where it is assumed that the normal points from
4608  side 0 to side 1. */
4609  flux[0] = penFace*(sol0[0] - sol1[0]);
4610  flux[1] = penFace*(sol0[1] - sol1[1]);
4611  flux[2] = penFace*(sol0[2] - sol1[2]);
4612  flux[3] = penFace*(sol0[3] - sol1[3]);
4613  flux[4] = penFace*(sol0[4] - sol1[4]);
4614  }
4615 
4616  break;
4617  }
4618  }
4619 }
4620 
4621 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::SymmetrizingFluxesFace(const unsigned short indFaceChunk,
4622  const unsigned short nInt,
4623  const unsigned short NPad,
4624  const su2double *solInt0,
4625  const su2double *solInt1,
4626  const su2double *viscosityInt0,
4627  const su2double *viscosityInt1,
4628  const su2double *kOverCvInt0,
4629  const su2double *kOverCvInt1,
4630  const su2double *metricNormalsFace,
4631  su2double *symmFluxes) {
4632 
4633  /* Constant ratio of the second viscosity and the viscosity itself. */
4634  const su2double lambdaOverMu = -TWO3;
4635 
4636  /*--- Set two factors such that either the original or the transposed diffusion
4637  tensor is taken in the symmetrizing fluxes. ---*/
4638 
4639  /* Use the following line for the original formulation. */
4640  const su2double alpha = lambdaOverMu;
4641 
4642  /* Use the following line for the transposed formulation. */
4643  //const su2double alpha = 1.0;
4644 
4645  /* Other constants, which appear in the symmetrizing fluxes. */
4646  const su2double beta = lambdaOverMu + 1.0 - alpha;
4647  const su2double alphaP1 = alpha + 1.0;
4648  const su2double lambdaP1 = lambdaOverMu + 1.0;
4649 
4650  /* Make a distinction between two and three space dimensions
4651  in order to have the most efficient code. */
4652  switch( nDim ) {
4653 
4654  case 2: {
4655 
4656  /*--- 2D simulation. Loop over the number of integration points
4657  of the face. ---*/
4658  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4659 
4660  /* Easier storage of the variables for this integration point. */
4661  const unsigned short offPointer = NPad*i + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4662  const su2double *sol0 = solInt0 + offPointer;
4663  const su2double *sol1 = solInt1 + offPointer;
4664  const su2double *normal = metricNormalsFace + i*(nDim+1);
4665 
4666  su2double *flux = symmFluxes + i*nDim*NPad + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4667 
4668  /* Determine the difference in conservative variables. Multiply these
4669  differences by the length of the normal vector to obtain the correct
4670  dimensions for the symmetrizing fluxes. */
4671  const su2double dSol[] = {normal[2]*(sol0[0] - sol1[0]),
4672  normal[2]*(sol0[1] - sol1[1]),
4673  normal[2]*(sol0[2] - sol1[2]),
4674  normal[2]*(sol0[3] - sol1[3])};
4675 
4676  /*--- Compute the terms that occur in the symmetrizing fluxes
4677  for state 0 and state 1. ---*/
4678  const unsigned short ind = indFaceChunk*nInt + i;
4679 
4680  const su2double DensityInv0 = 1.0/sol0[0], DensityInv1 = 1.0/sol1[0];
4681  const su2double Etot0 = DensityInv0*sol0[3], Etot1 = DensityInv1*sol1[3];
4682  const su2double nu0 = DensityInv0*viscosityInt0[ind], nu1 = DensityInv1*viscosityInt1[ind];
4683  const su2double kScal0 = DensityInv0*kOverCvInt0[ind], kScal1 = DensityInv1*kOverCvInt1[ind];
4684 
4685  const su2double vel0[] = {DensityInv0*sol0[1], DensityInv0*sol0[2]};
4686  const su2double vel1[] = {DensityInv1*sol1[1], DensityInv1*sol1[2]};
4687 
4688  const su2double velNorm0 = vel0[0]*normal[0] + vel0[1]*normal[1];
4689  const su2double velNorm1 = vel1[0]*normal[0] + vel1[1]*normal[1];
4690 
4691  const su2double velSquared0 = vel0[0]*vel0[0] + vel0[1]*vel0[1];
4692  const su2double velSquared1 = vel1[0]*vel1[0] + vel1[1]*vel1[1];
4693 
4694  /*--- Compute the average of the terms that occur in the symmetrizing
4695  fluxes. The average of the left and right terms is taken, rather
4696  than the terms evaluated at the average state, because the viscous
4697  fluxes are also computed as the average of the fluxes and not the
4698  fluxes of the averaged state. ---*/
4699  const su2double nuAvg = 0.5*(nu0 + nu1);
4700  const su2double kScalAvg = 0.5*(kScal0 + kScal1);
4701  const su2double nuVelSquaredAvg = 0.5*(nu0*velSquared0 + nu1*velSquared1);
4702  const su2double nuVelNormAve = 0.5*(nu0*velNorm0 + nu1*velNorm1);
4703  const su2double kScalEminVelSquaredAve = 0.5*(kScal0*(Etot0-velSquared0)
4704  + kScal1*(Etot1-velSquared1));
4705 
4706  const su2double nuVelAvg[] = {0.5*(nu0*vel0[0] + nu1*vel1[0]),
4707  0.5*(nu0*vel0[1] + nu1*vel1[1])};
4708  const su2double kScalVelAvg[] = {0.5*(kScal0*vel0[0] + kScal1*vel1[0]),
4709  0.5*(kScal0*vel0[1] + kScal1*vel1[1])};
4710  const su2double nuVelVelAvg[] = {0.5*(nu0*vel0[0]*velNorm0 + nu1*vel1[0]*velNorm1),
4711  0.5*(nu0*vel0[1]*velNorm0 + nu1*vel1[1]*velNorm1)};
4712 
4713  /*--- Abbreviations to make the flux computations a bit more efficient. ---*/
4714  const su2double abv1 = normal[0] *dSol[1] + normal[1] *dSol[2];
4715  const su2double abv2 = nuVelAvg[0]*dSol[1] + nuVelAvg[1]*dSol[2];
4716 
4717  const su2double abv2kScal = kScalVelAvg[0]*dSol[1] + kScalVelAvg[1]*dSol[2];
4718 
4719  const su2double abv3 = beta*(nuAvg*abv1 - nuVelNormAve*dSol[0]);
4720  const su2double abv4 = kScalAvg*dSol[3] - abv2kScal
4721  - kScalEminVelSquaredAve*dSol[0] + abv2;
4722 
4723  /*--- Compute the symmetrizing fluxes in x-direction. ---*/
4724  flux[0] = 0.0;
4725  flux[1] = abv3 + alphaP1*normal[0]*(nuAvg*dSol[1] - nuVelAvg[0]*dSol[0]);
4726  flux[2] = nuAvg*(normal[0]*dSol[2] + alpha*normal[1]*dSol[1])
4727  - (normal[0]*nuVelAvg[1] + alpha*normal[1]*nuVelAvg[0])*dSol[0];
4728  flux[3] = normal[0]*abv4
4729  - (lambdaP1*nuVelVelAvg[0] + nuVelSquaredAvg*normal[0])*dSol[0]
4730  + alpha*nuVelNormAve*dSol[1] + beta*nuVelAvg[0]*abv1;
4731 
4732  /*--- Compute the symmetrizing fluxes in y-direction. */
4733  flux = flux + NPad;
4734  flux[0] = 0.0;
4735  flux[1] = nuAvg*(normal[1]*dSol[1] + alpha*normal[0]*dSol[2])
4736  - (normal[1]*nuVelAvg[0] + alpha*normal[0]*nuVelAvg[1])*dSol[0];
4737  flux[2] = abv3 + alphaP1*normal[1]*(nuAvg*dSol[2] - nuVelAvg[1]*dSol[0]);
4738  flux[3] = normal[1]*abv4
4739  - (lambdaP1*nuVelVelAvg[1] + nuVelSquaredAvg*normal[1])*dSol[0]
4740  + alpha*nuVelNormAve*dSol[2] + beta*nuVelAvg[1]*abv1;
4741  }
4742 
4743  break;
4744  }
4745 
4746  /*------------------------------------------------------------------------*/
4747 
4748  case 3: {
4749 
4750  /*--- 3D simulation. Loop over the number of integration points
4751  of the face. ---*/
4752  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4753 
4754  /* Easier storage of the variables for this integration point. */
4755  const unsigned short offPointer = NPad*i + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4756  const su2double *sol0 = solInt0 + offPointer;
4757  const su2double *sol1 = solInt1 + offPointer;
4758  const su2double *normal = metricNormalsFace + i*(nDim+1);
4759 
4760  su2double *flux = symmFluxes + i*nDim*NPad + nVar*indFaceChunk;
4761 
4762  /* Determine the difference in conservative variables. Multiply these
4763  differences by the length of the normal vector to obtain the correct
4764  dimensions for the symmetrizing fluxes. */
4765  const su2double dSol[] = {normal[3]*(sol0[0] - sol1[0]),
4766  normal[3]*(sol0[1] - sol1[1]),
4767  normal[3]*(sol0[2] - sol1[2]),
4768  normal[3]*(sol0[3] - sol1[3]),
4769  normal[3]*(sol0[4] - sol1[4])};
4770 
4771  /*--- Compute the terms that occur in the symmetrizing fluxes
4772  for state 0 and state 1. ---*/
4773  const unsigned short ind = indFaceChunk*nInt + i;
4774 
4775  const su2double DensityInv0 = 1.0/sol0[0], DensityInv1 = 1.0/sol1[0];
4776  const su2double Etot0 = DensityInv0*sol0[4], Etot1 = DensityInv1*sol1[4];
4777  const su2double nu0 = DensityInv0*viscosityInt0[ind], nu1 = DensityInv1*viscosityInt1[ind];
4778  const su2double kScal0 = DensityInv0*kOverCvInt0[ind], kScal1 = DensityInv1*kOverCvInt1[ind];
4779 
4780  const su2double vel0[] = {DensityInv0*sol0[1], DensityInv0*sol0[2], DensityInv0*sol0[3]};
4781  const su2double vel1[] = {DensityInv1*sol1[1], DensityInv1*sol1[2], DensityInv1*sol1[3]};
4782 
4783  const su2double velNorm0 = vel0[0]*normal[0] + vel0[1]*normal[1] + vel0[2]*normal[2];
4784  const su2double velNorm1 = vel1[0]*normal[0] + vel1[1]*normal[1] + vel1[2]*normal[2];
4785 
4786  const su2double velSquared0 = vel0[0]*vel0[0] + vel0[1]*vel0[1] + vel0[2]*vel0[2];
4787  const su2double velSquared1 = vel1[0]*vel1[0] + vel1[1]*vel1[1] + vel1[2]*vel1[2];
4788 
4789  /*--- Compute the average of the terms that occur in the symmetrizing
4790  fluxes. The average of the left and right terms is taken, rather
4791  than the terms evaluated at the average state, because the viscous
4792  fluxes are also computed as the average of the fluxes and not the
4793  fluxes of the averaged state. ---*/
4794  const su2double nuAvg = 0.5*(nu0 + nu1);
4795  const su2double kScalAvg = 0.5*(kScal0 + kScal1);
4796  const su2double nuVelSquaredAvg = 0.5*(nu0*velSquared0 + nu1*velSquared1);
4797  const su2double nuVelNormAve = 0.5*(nu0*velNorm0 + nu1*velNorm1);
4798  const su2double kScalEminVelSquaredAve = 0.5*(kScal0*(Etot0-velSquared0)
4799  + kScal1*(Etot1-velSquared1));
4800 
4801  const su2double nuVelAvg[] = {0.5*(nu0*vel0[0] + nu1*vel1[0]),
4802  0.5*(nu0*vel0[1] + nu1*vel1[1]),
4803  0.5*(nu0*vel0[2] + nu1*vel1[2])};
4804  const su2double kScalVelAvg[] = {0.5*(kScal0*vel0[0] + kScal1*vel1[0]),
4805  0.5*(kScal0*vel0[1] + kScal1*vel1[1]),
4806  0.5*(kScal0*vel0[2] + kScal1*vel1[2])};
4807  const su2double nuVelVelAvg[] = {0.5*(nu0*vel0[0]*velNorm0 + nu1*vel1[0]*velNorm1),
4808  0.5*(nu0*vel0[1]*velNorm0 + nu1*vel1[1]*velNorm1),
4809  0.5*(nu0*vel0[2]*velNorm0 + nu1*vel1[2]*velNorm1)};
4810 
4811  /*--- Abbreviations to make the flux computations a bit more efficient. ---*/
4812  const su2double abv1 = normal[0] *dSol[1] + normal[1] *dSol[2] + normal[2] *dSol[3];
4813  const su2double abv2 = nuVelAvg[0]*dSol[1] + nuVelAvg[1]*dSol[2] + nuVelAvg[2]*dSol[3];
4814 
4815  const su2double abv2kScal = kScalVelAvg[0]*dSol[1] + kScalVelAvg[1]*dSol[2]
4816  + kScalVelAvg[2]*dSol[3];
4817 
4818  const su2double abv3 = beta*(nuAvg*abv1 - nuVelNormAve*dSol[0]);
4819  const su2double abv4 = kScalAvg*dSol[4] - abv2kScal
4820  - kScalEminVelSquaredAve*dSol[0] + abv2;
4821 
4822  /*--- Compute the symmetrizing fluxes in x-direction. ---*/
4823  flux[0] = 0.0;
4824  flux[1] = abv3 + alphaP1*normal[0]*(nuAvg*dSol[1] - nuVelAvg[0]*dSol[0]);
4825  flux[2] = nuAvg*(normal[0]*dSol[2] + alpha*normal[1]*dSol[1])
4826  - (normal[0]*nuVelAvg[1] + alpha*normal[1]*nuVelAvg[0])*dSol[0];
4827  flux[3] = nuAvg*(normal[0]*dSol[3] + alpha*normal[2]*dSol[1])
4828  - (normal[0]*nuVelAvg[2] + alpha*normal[2]*nuVelAvg[0])*dSol[0];
4829  flux[4] = normal[0]*abv4
4830  - (lambdaP1*nuVelVelAvg[0] + nuVelSquaredAvg*normal[0])*dSol[0]
4831  + alpha*nuVelNormAve*dSol[1] + beta*nuVelAvg[0]*abv1;
4832 
4833  /*--- Compute the symmetrizing fluxes in y-direction. ---*/
4834  flux = flux + NPad;
4835  flux[0] = 0.0;
4836  flux[1] = nuAvg*(normal[1]*dSol[1] + alpha*normal[0]*dSol[2])
4837  - (normal[1]*nuVelAvg[0] + alpha*normal[0]*nuVelAvg[1])*dSol[0];
4838  flux[2] = abv3 + alphaP1*normal[1]*(nuAvg*dSol[2] - nuVelAvg[1]*dSol[0]);
4839  flux[3] = nuAvg*(normal[1]*dSol[3] + alpha*normal[2]*dSol[2])
4840  - (normal[1]*nuVelAvg[2] + alpha*normal[2]*nuVelAvg[1])*dSol[0];
4841  flux[4] = normal[1]*abv4
4842  - (lambdaP1*nuVelVelAvg[1] + nuVelSquaredAvg*normal[1])*dSol[0]
4843  + alpha*nuVelNormAve*dSol[2] + beta*nuVelAvg[1]*abv1;
4844 
4845  /*--- Compute the symmetrizing fluxes in z-direction. ---*/
4846  flux = flux + NPad;
4847  flux[0] = 0.0;
4848  flux[1] = nuAvg*(normal[2]*dSol[1] + alpha*normal[0]*dSol[3])
4849  - (normal[2]*nuVelAvg[0] + alpha*normal[0]*nuVelAvg[2])*dSol[0];
4850  flux[2] = nuAvg*(normal[2]*dSol[2] + alpha*normal[1]*dSol[3])
4851  - (normal[2]*nuVelAvg[1] + alpha*normal[1]*nuVelAvg[2])*dSol[0];
4852  flux[3] = abv3 + alphaP1*normal[2]*(nuAvg*dSol[3] - nuVelAvg[2]*dSol[0]);
4853  flux[4] = normal[2]*abv4
4854  - (lambdaP1*nuVelVelAvg[2] + nuVelSquaredAvg*normal[2])*dSol[0]
4855  + alpha*nuVelNormAve*dSol[3] + beta*nuVelAvg[2]*abv1;
4856  }
4857 
4858  break;
4859  }
4860  }
4861 }
4862 
4863 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::TransformSymmetrizingFluxes(const unsigned short indFaceChunk,
4864  const unsigned short nInt,
4865  const unsigned short NPad,
4866  const su2double halfTheta,
4867  const su2double *symmFluxes,
4868  const su2double *weights,
4869  const su2double *metricCoorFace,
4870  su2double *paramFluxes) {
4871 
4872  /*--- Transform the fluxes, such that they must be multiplied with the
4873  gradients w.r.t. the parametric coordinates rather than the
4874  Cartesian coordinates of the basis functions. This involves the
4875  multiplication with the metric terms. Also multiply the fluxes with
4876  their integration weights and -theta/2. The parameter theta is the
4877  parameter in the Interior Penalty formulation, the factor 1/2 comes in
4878  from the averaging and the minus sign is from the convention that the
4879  viscous fluxes come with a minus sign in this code. ---*/
4880 
4881  /* Make a distinction between two and three space dimensions
4882  in order to have the most efficient code. */
4883  switch( nDim ) {
4884 
4885  case 2: {
4886  /* Two-dimensional computation. Loop over the integration
4887  points to correct the fluxes. */
4888  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4889 
4890  /* Easier storage of the location where the the fluxes
4891  are stored for this integration point as well as an
4892  abbreviation for the integration weights time halfTheta. */
4893  const unsigned short offPointer = i*nDim*NPad + indFaceChunk*nVar;
4894  const su2double *fluxX = symmFluxes + offPointer;
4895  const su2double *fluxY = fluxX + NPad;
4896  const su2double wTheta = -halfTheta*weights[i];
4897  su2double *paramFlux = paramFluxes + offPointer;
4898 
4899  /* Compute the modified metric terms. */
4900  const su2double *metricTerms = metricCoorFace + 4*i; // The 4 is nDim*nDim;
4901  const su2double drdx = wTheta*metricTerms[0];
4902  const su2double drdy = wTheta*metricTerms[1];
4903  const su2double dsdx = wTheta*metricTerms[2];
4904  const su2double dsdy = wTheta*metricTerms[3];
4905 
4906  /* Parametric fluxes in r-direction. */
4907  paramFlux[0] = fluxX[0]*drdx + fluxY[0]*drdy;
4908  paramFlux[1] = fluxX[1]*drdx + fluxY[1]*drdy;
4909  paramFlux[2] = fluxX[2]*drdx + fluxY[2]*drdy;
4910  paramFlux[3] = fluxX[3]*drdx + fluxY[3]*drdy;
4911 
4912  /* Parametric fluxes in s-direction. */
4913  paramFlux = paramFlux + NPad;
4914  paramFlux[0] = fluxX[0]*dsdx + fluxY[0]*dsdy;
4915  paramFlux[1] = fluxX[1]*dsdx + fluxY[1]*dsdy;
4916  paramFlux[2] = fluxX[2]*dsdx + fluxY[2]*dsdy;
4917  paramFlux[3] = fluxX[3]*dsdx + fluxY[3]*dsdy;
4918  }
4919 
4920  break;
4921  }
4922 
4923  case 3: {
4924  /* Three-dimensional computation. Loop over the integration
4925  points to correct the fluxes. */
4926  for(unsigned short i=0; i<nInt; ++i) {
4927 
4928  /* Easier storage of the location where the the fluxes
4929  are stored for this integration point as well as an
4930  abbreviation for the integration weights time halfTheta. */
4931  const unsigned short offPointer = i*nDim*NPad + indFaceChunk*nVar;
4932  const su2double *fluxX = symmFluxes + offPointer;
4933  const su2double *fluxY = fluxX + NPad;
4934  const su2double *fluxZ = fluxY + NPad;
4935  const su2double wTheta = -halfTheta*weights[i];
4936  su2double *paramFlux = paramFluxes + offPointer;
4937 
4938  /* Compute the modified metric terms. */
4939  const su2double *metricTerms = metricCoorFace + 9*i; // The 9 is nDim*nDim;
4940  const su2double drdx = wTheta*metricTerms[0];
4941  const su2double drdy = wTheta*metricTerms[1];
4942  const su2double drdz = wTheta*metricTerms[2];
4943 
4944  const su2double dsdx = wTheta*metricTerms[3];
4945  const su2double dsdy = wTheta*metricTerms[4];
4946  const su2double dsdz = wTheta*metricTerms[5];
4947 
4948  const su2double dtdx = wTheta*metricTerms[6];
4949  const su2double dtdy = wTheta*metricTerms[7];
4950  const su2double dtdz = wTheta*metricTerms[8];
4951 
4952  /* Parametric fluxes in r-direction. */
4953  paramFlux[0] = fluxX[0]*drdx + fluxY[0]*drdy + fluxZ[0]*drdz;
4954  paramFlux[1] = fluxX[1]*drdx + fluxY[1]*drdy + fluxZ[1]*drdz;
4955  paramFlux[2] = fluxX[2]*drdx + fluxY[2]*drdy + fluxZ[2]*drdz;
4956  paramFlux[3] = fluxX[3]*drdx + fluxY[3]*drdy + fluxZ[3]*drdz;
4957  paramFlux[4] = fluxX[4]*drdx + fluxY[4]*drdy + fluxZ[4]*drdz;
4958 
4959  /* Parametric fluxes in s-direction. */
4960  paramFlux = paramFlux + NPad;
4961  paramFlux[0] = fluxX[0]*dsdx + fluxY[0]*dsdy + fluxZ[0]*dsdz;
4962  paramFlux[1] = fluxX[1]*dsdx + fluxY[1]*dsdy + fluxZ[1]*dsdz;
4963  paramFlux[2] = fluxX[2]*dsdx + fluxY[2]*dsdy + fluxZ[2]*dsdz;
4964  paramFlux[3] = fluxX[3]*dsdx + fluxY[3]*dsdy + fluxZ[3]*dsdz;
4965  paramFlux[4] = fluxX[4]*dsdx + fluxY[4]*dsdy + fluxZ[4]*dsdz;
4966 
4967  /* Parametric fluxes in t-direction. */
4968  paramFlux = paramFlux + NPad;
4969  paramFlux[0] = fluxX[0]*dtdx + fluxY[0]*dtdy + fluxZ[0]*dtdz;
4970  paramFlux[1] = fluxX[1]*dtdx + fluxY[1]*dtdy + fluxZ[1]*dtdz;
4971  paramFlux[2] = fluxX[2]*dtdx + fluxY[2]*dtdy + fluxZ[2]*dtdz;
4972  paramFlux[3] = fluxX[3]*dtdx + fluxY[3]*dtdy + fluxZ[3]*dtdz;
4973  paramFlux[4] = fluxX[4]*dtdx + fluxY[4]*dtdy + fluxZ[4]*dtdz;
4974  }
4975 
4976  break;
4977  }
4978  }
4979 }
4980 
4981 void CFEM_DG_NSSolver::BC_Euler_Wall(CConfig *config,
4982  const unsigned long surfElemBeg,
4983  const unsigned long surfElemEnd,
4984  const CSurfaceElementFEM *surfElem,
4985  su2double *resFaces,
4986  CNumerics *conv_numerics,
4987  su2double *workArray){
4988 
4989  /* Initialization of the counter in resFaces. */
4990  unsigned long indResFaces = 0;
4991 
4992  /* Determine the number of faces that are treated simultaneously
4993  in the matrix products to obtain good gemm performance. */
4994  const unsigned short nPadInput = config->GetSizeMatMulPadding();
4995  const unsigned short nFaceSimul = nPadInput/nVar;
4996 
4997  /* Determine the minimum padded size in the matrix multiplications, which
4998  corresponds to 64 byte alignment. */
4999  const unsigned short nPadMin = 64/sizeof(passivedouble);
5000 
5001  /*--- Loop over the requested range of surface faces. Multiple faces
5002  are treated simultaneously to improve the performance of the matrix
5003  multiplications. As a consequence, the update of the counter l
5004  happens at the end of this loop section. ---*/
5005  for(unsigned long l=surfElemBeg; l<surfElemEnd;) {
5006 
5007  /* Determine the end index for this chunk of faces and the padded
5008  N value in the gemm computations. */
5009  unsigned long lEnd;
5010  unsigned short ind, llEnd, NPad;
5011 
5012  MetaDataChunkOfElem(surfElem, l, surfElemEnd, nFaceSimul,
5013  nPadMin, lEnd, ind, llEnd, NPad);
5014 
5015  /*--- Get the information from the standard element, which is the same
5016  for all the faces in the chunks considered. ---*/
5017  const unsigned short nInt = standardBoundaryFacesSol[ind].GetNIntegration();
5018 
5019  /*--- Set the pointers for the local arrays. ---*/
5020  su2double *solIntL = workArray;
5021  su2double *solIntR = solIntL + NPad*nInt;
5022  su2double *work = solIntR + NPad*nInt;
5023 
5024  /* Compute the left states in the integration points of the chunk of
5025  faces. The array workarray is used as temporary storage inside the
5026  function LeftStatesIntegrationPointsBoundaryFace. */
5027  LeftStatesIntegrationPointsBoundaryFace(config, llEnd, NPad, &surfElem[l],
5028  work, solIntL);
5029 
5030  /* Compute the right state by applying the inviscid wall BC's. */
5031  BoundaryStates_Euler_Wall(config, llEnd, NPad, &surfElem[l],
5032  solIntL, solIntR);
5033 
5034  /* The remainder of the boundary treatment is the same for all
5035  boundary conditions (except the symmetry plane). */
5036  ViscousBoundaryFacesBCTreatment(config, conv_numerics, llEnd, NPad,
5037  0.0, false, 0.0, false, &surfElem[l],
5038  solIntL, solIntR, work, resFaces,
5039  indResFaces, nullptr);
5040 
5041  /* Update the value of the counter l to the end index of the
5042  current chunk. */
5043  l = lEnd;
5044  }
5045 }
